%N A389650 Minimal integer s such that the ceiling of the Golomb-Keller limit gives prime(n+1) (see comment).
%C A389650 The Golomb-Keller formula expresses prime(n+1) as a limit: prime(n+1) = lim_{s->oo} (zeta(s)*Product_{j=1..n}(1-1/prime(j)^s) - 1)^(-1/s). Here a(n) is the smallest positive integer s such that ceiling(h(s)) = prime(n+1) where h(s) = (zeta(s)*Product_{j=1..n}(1-1/prime(j)^s) - 1)^(-1/s).
%C A389650 Peaks in a(n)/prime(n) correlate strongly with twin prime configurations.
%H A389650 Benoit Cloitre, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2508.02690">An effective analytic recurrence for prime numbers</a>, arXiv:2508.02690v2 [math.NT], Oct. 2025.
%H A389650 Benoit Cloitre, <a href="/A389650/a389650.png">Plot of a(n)/prime(n) for n=1 up to 200</a>.
%H A389650 S. W. Golomb, <a href="https://projecteuclid.org/journals/pacific-journal-of-mathematics/volume-63/issue-2/Formulas-for-the-next-prime/pjm/1102867397.full">Formulas for the next prime</a>, Pacific J. Math. 63, (1976).
%H A389650 J. B. Keller, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0711.3940">A recursion equation for prime numbers</a>, arXiv:0711.3940 [math.NT], 2007-2008.
%F A389650 a(n) >= 2 for all n >= 1.
%F A389650 a(n) <= prime(n) for all n >= 1 (using Nagura's theorem).
%F A389650 liminf_{n->oo} a(n)/prime(n) = 0 (by Westzynthius's theorem).
%F A389650 limsup_{n->oo} a(n)/prime(n) = C <= 0.4332 (using Dusart's bounds).
%F A389650 Under the twin prime conjecture, C > log(psi) = 0.3823, where psi = 1.46557 is the supergolden ratio (A092526).
%F A389650 For any c > 0.596, a(n) <= c*prime(n) for all sufficiently large n (proven). Conjectured: this holds for any c > C.
%e A389650 For n=6: The first 6 primes are 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13. We seek prime(7) = 17.
%e A389650 With s=7: h(7) = 15.856..., so ceiling(15.856) = 16 != 17.
%e A389650 With s=8: h(8) = 16.125..., so ceiling(16.125) = 17. Thus a(6) = 8.
%o A389650 (PARI) \\ Use: default(realprecision, 2000);
%o A389650 a(n) = {
%o A389650   my(pnext = prime(n+1), s = 2, P, Dn, h);
%o A389650   while(1,
%o A389650     P = 1.0;
%o A389650     for(j = 1, n, P *= (1.0 - 1.0/prime(j)^s));
%o A389650     Dn = zeta(s) * P;
%o A389650     h = (Dn - 1.0)^(-1.0/s);
%o A389650     if(ceil(h) == pnext, return(s));
%o A389650     s++;
%o A389650     if(s > prime(n), error("exceeded prime(n)"));
%o A389650   );
%o A389650 }
